GERMANY: A Costly Budgetary Fetish
FRAANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing intense criticism in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
Germany, in fact, insisted that this principle be incorporated into the criteria set out in the Maastricht Treaty, which defines the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), granting independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone entailed a shift in political governance.
Thus, during the referendum on the ratification of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, the independence of the Banque de France was one of the strongest arguments against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, it has become commonplace, if you will, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schäuble, regularly comments on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schäuble's comments target the very core of what constitutes central bank independence.
If he does not seek to redefine the monetary policy objective (that "price stability," in the old Bundesbank jargon), he nonetheless offers advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such a goal.
We have known precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then German Minister of Finance, offered his advice to the first President of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was to ultimately create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typically Dutch reticence, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing an opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Nevertheless – he added –, it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."

The respect for monetary policy independence has long been a central element of Germany's Stabilitätkultur (culture of stability).
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's exhortations in 1956 to contain interest rate hikes.
At this time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the verge of creating the Fifth Republic, with a Banque de France reporting to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following various crises that have shaken the EMU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Has the old dogma become obsolete?
The Eurozone remains highly vulnerable; the median EU resident has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming, we are close to the critical situation.
Yet, the United States are doing better.
Despite a difficult-to-manage political deadlock, they have managed to address the macro-economic problem (the weakness of global demand) by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States also handled their banking problems better, which were initially much more severe than in Europe.
There is, of course, a strong interaction between measures that can be taken in both areas.
More robust an economy is, more profitable its banks are, and the better they can fulfill their function: financing the economy.
But the ECB's independence is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of public support.
Indeed, the famous independence of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the continuous support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
This is exactly the opposite case with the ECB.
Voces are being heard, particularly in Germany, calling for increasing pressure on it.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden placed upon its shoulders.
The less budgetary policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are, in fact, constrained to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course and allow the economy to languish, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression towards nationalism, both right and left, in all countries of the EMU, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And Germany leads the way, with its obsession with the schwarze Null, the balanced budget, against all odds.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably, not only from an arithmetic perspective but also morally, even though this defies economic sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the leading German public finance experts, such as Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, developed a "golden rule" according to which recurrent spending should be financed, on average, by recurrent revenues.
Public expenditures and the resources they require are justified by their utility.
This means that investments aimed at enhancing productivity—capital expenditures—can be financed with debt, whose repayment is ensured by the growth of revenues and the tax base associated with them.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
This is crucial because in Germany, around 50% of public investment spending is managed at this level (a proportion that is decreasing, since the municipal share was two-thirds in the early 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with the support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittlestand).
However, compared to the early 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenditures have fallen by about 15%.
This has been true for more than a decade now, and they are insufficient to maintain the stock of capital.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, then we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In brief, the schwarze Null goes against the goal sought.
Aged infrastructure (though not as much as in the United States) has become a real issue for Germany.
Moreover, the fiscal frugality of German leaders spills over beyond Germany’s borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to adapt to national peculiarities.
Naturally, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But transforming the European Central Bank, the only institution willing to "do what is necessary" to get the EMU back on track, into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
For states where fiscal space exists, using it to ease pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without any doubt, enjoys a certain margin of maneuver in this regard.
